       =20
       =20


<div class=3D"f--field f--richtext">

   =20
   =20
    <p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Zombies may be fictional monsters =
best portrayed by Hollywood and avid trick-or-treaters on Halloween.</span>=
</p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">But how would we actually fare against=
 a horde of the undead?</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Probably not well, according to Tim Fr=
azier, professor and faculty director of the School of Continuing Studies=
=E2=80=99 </span><a href=3D"https://scs.georgetown.edu/programs/419/master-=
of-professional-studies-in-emergency-and-disaster-management/"><span style=
=3D"font-weight: 400;">Emergency and Disaster Management program</span></a>=
<span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">. It would only be a matter of days befor=
e zombies would overwhelm human society, said Frazier, who is an expert on =
coastal hazards and researches methods to help communities build resilience=
 to natural hazards and climate change.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">In the spirit of Halloween, we asked F=
razier how he would apply best practices from the field in a zombie apocaly=
pse =E2=80=93 and where he would most like to hunker down.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Here=E2=80=99s his survival guide to o=
utlast the walking dead.</span></p>



</div><!-- f--field f--richtext -->


    </div><!-- c--component c--article-body-text -->

</div><!-- cc--component-container cc--article-body-text -->



 =20
   =20

<div class=3D"cc--component-container cc--article-body-text  ">

    <div class=3D"c--component c--article-body-text">

       =20
       =20


<div class=3D"f--field f--richtext">

   =20
   =20
    <h2 style=3D"text-align: center;">Ask a Professor: Tim Frazier on Disas=
ter Management, Zombies and Survival Tips</h2>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;">&nbsp; <iframe title=3D"YouTube video play=
er" src=3D"cid:frame-638A4539DA80A0437EB62855083E8C89@mhtml.blink" width=3D=
"560" height=3D"315" frameborder=3D"0" allowfullscreen=3D"allowfullscreen">=
</iframe></p>
<p style=3D"text-align: left;"><i><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Editor=
=E2=80=99s note: This interview has been edited for length and clarity.</sp=
an></i></p>
<h3>In emergency situations, how should people generally respond?</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">One of the things we say in the field =
is that the first responder is not the first responder. In reality, the fir=
st responder is the first person to respond to the crisis event, which typi=
cally is the population in the area. What we tell people is you need to be =
your own first responder, so you need to be prepared at home to manage unti=
l help arrives.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">The second thing we say is listen to t=
he people in charge. In the =E2=80=9850s, =E2=80=9960s and into the =E2=80=
=9880s, when the emergency manager or the police or fire department told yo=
u to do something, you did it. Today, the difference in our society is that=
 everybody is their own emergency manager. Something happens, and they want=
 to explore.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">The reality is they=E2=80=99re pulling=
 in information from multiple sources. They go to the web, they Google, the=
y look at their phone for Instagram or whatever and make their own emergenc=
y management decision. Sometimes, that decision is good, sometimes it=E2=80=
=99s bad. It doesn=E2=80=99t always align with what a local official is tel=
ling you to do.</span></p>
<h3>What mistakes do civilians often make in emergencies?</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">You might have a basic instinct that p=
uts you at risk, and you should avoid those circumstances. If you can=E2=80=
=99t swim, don=E2=80=99t jump in the water to try to save someone. Understa=
nd the situation and your opportunity or ability to contribute to a positiv=
e response, and understand the limitations for you to make the response eve=
n worse by contributing in ways that aren=E2=80=99t good.</span></p>
<h3>How do emergency managers determine how many resources should be devote=
d to a crisis?</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">We call [emergencies] a risk or hazard=
, and then it becomes a disaster. One of the key definitions we use to desc=
ribe a disaster is when we have an event that overwhelms the ability of the=
 local community to effectively respond to that event. We keep bringing in =
those response resources from our friends in the field until we get to the =
point where we can adequately handle the crisis event.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">When [everyone] is overwhelmed, you=E2=
=80=99re just overwhelmed, and you have to deal with it yourself. The only =
way to deal with being under-resourced and overwhelmed is to take away from=
 someone else who needs those resources as well. You=E2=80=99re competing f=
or resources everybody needs.&nbsp;</span></p>
<h3>How long would it take for a zombie outbreak to become a disaster?</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Days, not weeks. There will be a point=
 in a zombie apocalypse where if it=E2=80=99s cascading outward and we=E2=
=80=99re becoming overwhelmed, people will realize, =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m on=
 my own.=E2=80=9D You can predict the spread and impact based on global con=
nectivity and networks and flows of goods and services, including people.</=
span></p>
<h3>How would a response to a zombie apocalypse differ from other crises?</=
h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Our golden rule in emergency managemen=
t is to save lives first. What are the measures necessary to save lives, an=
d how does that change from one hazard stressor to another? For a zombie si=
tuation, the stressor would be, =E2=80=9CI have to put down the zombie beca=
use I=E2=80=99m saving lives by putting the zombie down.=E2=80=9D You=E2=80=
=99re preventing them from joining the other team by saving lives.</span></=
p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">There=E2=80=99s also a lot of basic pr=
inciples. You want to quarantine the area as best you can. You want to isol=
ate the challenge and the problem. You want to bring an efficient and effec=
tive level of resources to bear to minimize the negative impacts of those p=
roblems. Once you get those negative and immediate life-threatening impacts=
 minimized, then you move into recovery mode.</span></p>
<h3>What are the essential supplies you=E2=80=99d need in a zombie apocalyp=
se?</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Normally, you go for water first becau=
se you can survive three to five days on water alone. Then, obviously food.=
 Then you think about medical supplies and other things like how to generat=
e electricity or batteries to know what=E2=80=99s going on. You go from the=
 basic needs to the luxury needs or items that might help you survive longe=
r-term.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">You need to get the thing that saves y=
our life first and foremost. In a zombie situation, I think the first thing=
 you go for is some sort of weapon to protect yourself. You=E2=80=99re not =
surviving against the elements, you=E2=80=99re surviving against an aggress=
or. Once I stop the attacker, then I look around and say, =E2=80=9CWhat res=
ources do I have or need to sustain myself until the cavalry comes over the=
 hill?=E2=80=9D</span></p>
<h3>Would you rather be stationary or on the move?</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">There are multiple challenges with bei=
ng on the move. Part of the calculus is I don=E2=80=99t know the area very =
well. I don=E2=80=99t know what=E2=80=99s going on. When you=E2=80=99re in =
an area you=E2=80=99re not normally in and familiar with, you lack informat=
ion, which can be incredibly damaging from your survival perspective.</span=
></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">The other thing about being on the mov=
e is that your exposure is increased. You don=E2=80=99t have a safe place t=
o hunker down or hide. You don=E2=80=99t have the bunker that you close the=
 door to so no one else is going in. You don=E2=80=99t necessarily have the=
 defensive posture position like the castle with a moat.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">The last thing I would say is you=E2=
=80=99re limited in the amount of resources you can have at your disposal b=
ecause you can=E2=80=99t carry a lot of resources when you=E2=80=99re walki=
ng, even in a car.</span></p>
<h3>Is it better to be in a rural or urban environment in the case of zombi=
es?</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">I think the most effective argument is=
 a rural area. There=E2=80=99s less potential for aggressors. If you=E2=80=
=99re someone who lives in a rural area in our country, there=E2=80=99s a l=
ikelihood you have some sort of weapon.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">I=E2=80=99m overgeneralizing, but a lo=
t of people who live in rural environments have this understanding that the=
y have to take care of themselves on a daily basis. If hell comes, it=E2=80=
=99s got to be really bad for people. If you=E2=80=99re in the mountains of=
 Montana and there=E2=80=99s a blizzard, nobody=E2=80=99s coming, right? Yo=
u=E2=80=99re on your own until the situation gets to the point where somebo=
dy has the opportunity to come.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">You=E2=80=99re much better off than if=
 you live in a one-bedroom apartment in the middle of New York City where e=
verybody is turning into zombies. Give me the country.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Urban areas can be better from a respo=
nse perspective because they=E2=80=99re getting their resources faster. But=
 if you can survive without that resource, then [the city] could be much wo=
rse as you=E2=80=99re competing for other survival resources.</span></p>
<h3>What part of the U.S. would you want to be in during a zombie apocalyps=
e?</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Intermountain Northwest. Idaho, Montan=
a, one of those places with far less population density and a vast amount o=
f natural resources, from water in the stream you could purify and drink to=
 game you can hunt or fish for. There=E2=80=99s also a lack of proximity to=
 urban areas.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">I said Intermountain Northwest because=
 that=E2=80=99s more realistic. But if you could get to an island that has =
an abundant supply of water and potentially food, that=E2=80=99s where you =
want to be.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Smaller islands with some resources th=
at are uninhabited or have low populations. Fiji=E2=80=99s beautiful. There=
 are Pacific islands that look like that and don=E2=80=99t have any zombies=
 on them. I=E2=80=99ll say this tongue in cheek, hope for a zombie apocalyp=
se, get to an island somewhere in the Fiji chain, retire early, sit back an=
d enjoy the rest of your life while the world [ends.]</span></p>
<h3>In a rural area, would you rather be by yourself or part of a community=
 protecting each other?</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">If you have a group you trust relative=
ly well, there=E2=80=99s a level of ease associated with that, but there=E2=
=80=99s also a level of angst because you don=E2=80=99t know how that situa=
tion is going to unfold when push comes to shove.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">You go out to McDonald=E2=80=99s and g=
et a large fries. You=E2=80=99re sharing your fries at the table, and you b=
ought a large fries on purpose. It=E2=80=99s McDonald=E2=80=99s, everybody=
=E2=80=99s going to take a few fries, so just get a large. Don=E2=80=99t ge=
t a medium.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">I personally prefer to be on my own. I=
 know I=E2=80=99m competent and capable of handling that situation myself, =
and my level of trust for people trying to steal my fries [is low.]</span><=
/p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">I=E2=80=99m never the person who goes =
to McDonald=E2=80=99s and orders a medium and then whines and cries when pe=
ople take my fries. That=E2=80=99s not the mentality we have in the field o=
f emergency management. We obtain more resources than we need because we kn=
ow there=E2=80=99s going to be someone who=E2=80=99s going to need or take =
some of our resources.</span></p>



</div><!-- f--field f--richtext -->


    </div><!-- c--component c--article-body-text -->

</div><!-- cc--component-container cc--article-body-text -->





